        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "chore: migrate keyring from 99designs to byteness fork",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nReplaces `github.com/99designs/keyring` v1.2.2 with `github.com/byteness/keyring` v1.11.0 — an actively maintained fork. The original `99designs/keyring` has been effectively abandoned (last release Dec 2022, no commits since 2022), whereas `byteness/keyring` is actively maintained (v1.11.0, 42 releases) and API-compatible.\n\nThis is a pure import-path swap across 30 `.go` files plus `go.mod`/`go.sum`. The unused `github.com/99designs/go-keychain` indirect dependency is dropped; the byteness dependency tree brings in `github.com/byteness/go-keychain` as its maintained replacement.\n\n**This PR is preparation for 1Password support in gogcli.** `byteness/keyring` ships `op` / `op-connect` / `op-desktop` backends that the old `99designs/keyring` lacks. Wiring those backends into gogcli will follow in a separate PR; this change is the groundwork (dependency swap) that makes it possible.\n\n## Why\n\n- `99designs/keyring`: abandoned, last commit 2022.\n- `byteness/keyring`: maintained fork, full API compatibility, plus new backends (1Password, Windows Hello) — the motivation for switching.\n\n## Testing\n\n- `go build ./...` clean\n- Full `go test ./...` passes\n- Manually verified `gog auth list` / `gog auth tokens list` round-trip through the keyring after the swap\n\n## Follow-up\n\nA subsequent PR will add `gog auth keyring <op|op-connect|op-desktop>` to expose the 1Password backends unlocked by this dependency change.\n\n🤖 Generated with [Claude Code](https://claude.com/claude-code)",
